Three different measures

• Subjective hearing loss: Do you have a hearing loss? Yes, No
• Subjective hearing rating: Is your hearing, using a HA if you use one… Poor to Excellent
• Subjective hearing rating: Is your hearing, without a HA… Poor to Excellent

Regression (following Hamalainen et al 2021)

back to top

With 18 variables, participants are more likely to report subjective hearing loss if they:
• have a higher BPTA4 (13.8 vs 26.4)
• have greater PTA4 asymmetry (3.0 vs 7.2)
• have more difficulty understanding speech in noise (SSQ speech; 8.0 vs 6.5)

With variable selection, participants are more likely to report subjective hearing loss if they:
• have a higher BPTA4
• have more difficulty understanding speech in noise
• have any hearing device (?; 0% vs 34%)
• have greater PTA4 asymmetry

Compared with Hamalainen et al (2021)’s results:
• Similarities: Worse PTA, higher asymmetry, more trouble hearing in noise
• They found these effects, but we did not (or found weak effects): Age, male sex, device use, higher multimorbidity, better memory (higher PC scores), driving/good transport, social network index


Regression (our variables; overall scores)

back to top

With 24 variables, participants are more likely to report subjective hearing loss if they:
• have worse BPTA4 (14.1 vs 26.5)
• have more PTA asymmetry (2.9 vs 7.3)
• have worse overall SSQ scores (8.9 vs 7.6)
• have worse HHIE total scores (4.1 vs 13.2)
• have experienced tinnitus in the past week (15% vs 39%)
